{
  "phase": "question",
  "questions": [
    {
      "id": "q1",
      "question": "Should the D3 force-directed graph fully replace BayesNetGraph.tsx or coexist as an alternative view (e.g., toggle between static circular and force-directed layouts)?",
      "category": "requirements",
      "why_it_matters": "The task says 'replace or extend' — full replacement is simpler but breaks existing tests and the known-working static layout. Extending means maintaining two code paths."
    },
    {
      "id": "q2",
      "question": "Should we use a hybrid React+D3 approach (React owns the DOM, D3 handles math/simulation) or a D3-owns-the-DOM approach (D3 selections create/update SVG elements directly)?",
      "category": "design",
      "why_it_matters": "The codebase is pure React with inline styles. A hybrid approach preserves React idioms (hooks, component composition, CSS variables) but is more complex to wire up with d3-drag/d3-zoom. A D3-owns-DOM approach is simpler for interactions but fights React's rendering model and breaks the existing NodeWithDetail lazy-loading pattern."
    },
    {
      "id": "q3",
      "question": "How should the force simulation handle real-time data updates from the 5-second refetch interval on useMarkets without resetting node positions?",
      "category": "design",
      "why_it_matters": "The current hooks refetch every 5 seconds. Naively re-initializing the force simulation on each update would reset all node positions and animations, destroying the user's drag state and causing visual jitter."
    },
    {
      "id": "q4",
      "question": "What data source defines the directed edges (conditional dependencies) between markets? The current BayesNetGraph accepts an optional conditionalEdges prop, but MarketDetail passes only focusMarketId — where do edges come from at runtime?",
      "category": "codebase",
      "why_it_matters": "Without a clear edge data source, the force-directed graph would show disconnected nodes. The ConditionalEditor creates dependencies via useProbabilityEdit, but there's no visible API endpoint or hook that returns the full dependency graph. This affects whether edges can be rendered at all."
    },
    {
      "id": "q5",
      "question": "Should the clique overlay visualization remain as static rounded rectangles enclosing clique members, or should it adapt to the dynamic force layout (e.g., convex hull around clique nodes)?",
      "category": "design",
      "why_it_matters": "The current implementation draws clique overlays at fixed positions. In a force-directed layout, nodes move — so clique overlays need to dynamically recompute their bounds (convex hull or bounding box) as nodes are dragged or the simulation ticks, which adds significant complexity."
    },
    {
      "id": "q6",
      "question": "What should the node click callback signature look like for CPT editor integration? Should it open the ConditionalEditor inline, in a modal, or navigate to the market detail page?",
      "category": "requirements",
      "why_it_matters": "The task mentions 'node click callback for CPT editor integration' but the ConditionalEditor currently lives within the MarketDetail page and requires target/context variable IDs. The callback contract affects how tightly coupled the graph becomes to the trading feature."
    },
    {
      "id": "q7",
      "question": "Should d3 be installed as the full bundle ('d3') or as individual modules ('d3-force', 'd3-selection', 'd3-zoom', 'd3-drag')? Are there bundle size constraints?",
      "category": "requirements",
      "why_it_matters": "The full d3 package is ~500KB minified. Individual modules (d3-force + d3-selection + d3-zoom + d3-drag) total ~60KB. The current frontend has minimal dependencies — this choice significantly impacts bundle size."
    },
    {
      "id": "q8",
      "question": "How should the existing BayesNetGraph tests be handled? The current test suite mocks useMarkets/useEngineStats and asserts on specific SVG elements and text content.",
      "category": "codebase",
      "why_it_matters": "D3 force simulations are asynchronous and DOM-manipulating, making the existing synchronous render-and-assert tests invalid. We need to decide whether to rewrite tests for D3, use snapshot testing, or test the simulation logic separately from rendering."
    }
  ],
  "assumptions": [
    {
      "id": "a1",
      "assumption": "We will use individual D3 modules (d3-force, d3-selection, d3-zoom, d3-drag) rather than the full d3 bundle to minimize bundle size.",
      "confidence": 0.8,
      "if_wrong": "Need to install the full d3 package instead; no architectural impact, just a different import pattern and larger bundle."
    },
    {
      "id": "a2",
      "assumption": "A hybrid React+D3 approach is preferred: React renders SVG elements, D3 handles force simulation math, zoom transforms, and drag behavior via useEffect hooks.",
      "confidence": 0.7,
      "if_wrong": "If D3-owns-DOM is preferred, we'd need to restructure away from React components for nodes/edges and lose the NodeWithDetail lazy-loading pattern."
    },
    {
      "id": "a3",
      "assumption": "The existing useMarkets and useEngineStats hooks provide all necessary data — no new API endpoints are needed.",
      "confidence": 0.85,
      "if_wrong": "May need a dedicated graph/topology API endpoint that returns nodes and edges together, especially for conditional dependency edges."
    },
    {
      "id": "a4",
      "assumption": "Conditional edges (directed dependencies) are derivable from the clique structure returned by useEngineStats — nodes sharing a clique have edges between them.",
      "confidence": 0.4,
      "if_wrong": "Cliques represent groups, not directed edges. We'd need an explicit dependency/edge API or the conditionalEdges prop to be populated from somewhere. This is a significant gap."
    },
    {
      "id": "a5",
      "assumption": "The component should be a full replacement of BayesNetGraph.tsx, not a separate component, to avoid maintaining two graph implementations.",
      "confidence": 0.7,
      "if_wrong": "Would need to add a toggle mechanism and keep both implementations, increasing maintenance burden."
    },
    {
      "id": "a6",
      "assumption": "Responsive sizing means the SVG fills its container and responds to window resize events, similar to the current viewBox approach.",
      "confidence": 0.9,
      "if_wrong": "If responsive means specific breakpoint-based layouts, the force simulation parameters would need to change at different screen sizes."
    },
    {
      "id": "a7",
      "assumption": "The node click callback will be a simple onNodeClick(marketId: string) prop, leaving the parent component to decide navigation or modal behavior.",
      "confidence": 0.75,
      "if_wrong": "If the graph needs to embed the CPT editor directly, the component becomes much more complex with internal state management for editing."
    }
  ],
  "spawn_children": false,
  "children": []
}

{
  "phase": "research",
  "answers": [
    {
      "question_id": "q1",
      "answer": "Full replacement is the right approach. BayesNetGraph is used in exactly one place (MarketDetail.tsx line 62, passing only focusMarketId). There is no toggle mechanism, no other consumer, and the component is self-contained with its own data fetching. Replacing in-place avoids maintaining two graph implementations. The existing tests (11 scenarios in BayesNetGraph.test.tsx) will need rewriting regardless since the rendering model changes fundamentally.",
      "confidence": 0.85,
      "evidence": [
        "frontend/src/routes/MarketDetail.tsx:62",
        "frontend/src/features/graph/BayesNetGraph.tsx:227-229",
        "frontend/src/__tests__/BayesNetGraph.test.tsx:1-332"
      ],
      "uncertainty": "Whether stakeholders have a strong preference for keeping the static layout as a fallback. The circular layout is simpler to reason about for small networks."
    },
    {
      "question_id": "q2",
      "answer": "Hybrid React+D3 approach is strongly preferred. The codebase is pure React with inline styles, React Query hooks (TanStack v5.60), and component composition patterns. NodeWithDetail (BayesNetGraph.tsx:212-225) uses useMarket() per node for lazy data loading — this pattern requires React to own the DOM. D3 should handle force simulation math (d3-force), zoom transforms (d3-zoom via useEffect on SVG ref), and drag behavior (d3-drag via useEffect on node refs). React renders SVG elements and manages state; D3 computes positions and handles interactions.",
      "confidence": 0.9,
      "evidence": [
        "frontend/src/features/graph/BayesNetGraph.tsx:212-225",
        "frontend/src/lib/query/hooks.ts:48-54",
        "frontend/package.json:dependencies"
      ],
      "uncertainty": "d3-drag and d3-zoom integration with React's synthetic event system can be tricky — may need useRef + useEffect wiring that bypasses React's event delegation."
    },
    {
      "question_id": "q3",
      "answer": "Keep the d3.forceSimulation instance in a useRef, not in state. On data refetch (every 5s from useMarkets), diff the incoming market list against current simulation nodes: (1) add new nodes at centroid position with zero velocity, (2) remove departed nodes, (3) update data properties (title, status, probability) on existing nodes without touching x/y/vx/vy. Call simulation.nodes(updatedNodes) and simulation.alpha(0.1).restart() with a low alpha to gently re-settle without full reset. For links, similarly diff and call forceLink.links(). The NodeWithDetail per-node useMarket(node.id) calls also refetch at 5s — these update visual properties (marginals, outcomes) without affecting simulation positions at all since they only change the detail prop.",
      "confidence": 0.85,
      "evidence": [
        "frontend/src/lib/query/hooks.ts:48-54",
        "frontend/src/lib/query/hooks.ts:56-65",
        "frontend/src/features/graph/BayesNetGraph.tsx:212-225"
      ],
      "uncertainty": "The exact alpha restart value needs tuning. Too high causes visual jitter on every refetch; too low means new nodes don't settle properly. May need alphaDecay tuning as well."
    },
    {
      "question_id": "q4",
      "answer": "There is NO API endpoint or hook that returns directed conditional dependency edges. The conditionalEdges prop on BayesNetGraph is defined (GraphEdge interface at BayesNetGraph.tsx:16-20) and fully rendered when provided, but MarketDetail.tsx never passes it (line 62 only passes focusMarketId). Conditional dependencies are created via useProbabilityEdit and stored server-side in CONDITIONAL_MARGINALS dict (backend/server.py:223, 3489-3510) keyed by context_state_key format 'variableId=outcomeId|...', but there's no GET endpoint to retrieve these relationships. Cliques from useEngineStats provide undirected groupings (which variables participate in the same factor), NOT directed conditional edges. To show edges, either: (a) add a new API endpoint that returns edges from CONDITIONAL_MARGINALS, or (b) infer undirected connections from clique membership (any two nodes in the same clique share an edge — but this loses directionality).",
      "confidence": 0.9,
      "evidence": [
        "frontend/src/features/graph/BayesNetGraph.tsx:16-27",
        "frontend/src/routes/MarketDetail.tsx:62",
        "backend/server.py:223",
        "backend/server.py:3303-3311",
        "backend/server.py:3489-3510",
        "frontend/src/lib/api/types.ts:105-151"
      ],
      "uncertainty": "Whether the CONDITIONAL_MARGINALS data structure captures enough information to reconstruct directed edges (it stores context→target relationships which ARE directed edges). Need to verify if this dict is always populated or only after explicit user edits."
    },
    {
      "question_id": "q5",
      "answer": "Clique overlays must adapt to the dynamic layout. The current CliqueOverlay (BayesNetGraph.tsx:171-210) computes a static bounding box from fixed node positions. In a force-directed layout, nodes move during simulation ticks and user drags, so the overlay must recompute on every frame. Recommended approach: compute the convex hull of member node positions on each simulation tick using a simple gift-wrapping algorithm (O(nh) for small cliques), then render as an SVG path with rounded corners and padding. This is computationally cheap since cliques are typically 2-5 nodes. A simpler fallback is a dynamic bounding box (min/max of member node x/y + padding), which works well for small cliques but looks awkward for non-convex arrangements.",
      "confidence": 0.8,
      "evidence": [
        "frontend/src/features/graph/BayesNetGraph.tsx:171-210",
        "frontend/src/features/graph/BayesNetGraph.tsx:285-287"
      ],
      "uncertainty": "Whether convex hull or bounding box is visually better. Convex hull is more accurate but bounding box is simpler and may suffice for typical 2-4 node cliques. Also unclear if clique overlays should animate smoothly or snap to new positions."
    },
    {
      "question_id": "q6",
      "answer": "The callback should be a simple onNodeClick(marketId: string) prop, with the parent component deciding the action. Current architecture supports this: MarketDetail is at route /markets/:id, and ConditionalEditor (ConditionalEditor.tsx:1-289) requires a full Market object and is deeply embedded in the trading workflow (needs session, account, outcome selection UI). The graph component should NOT embed the CPT editor — it should navigate to the market detail page via react-router-dom. The parent (MarketDetail) can use navigate(`/markets/${marketId}`) to switch focus. This keeps the graph component decoupled from trading features and consistent with the existing architecture where BayesNetGraph is a visualization-only component.",
      "confidence": 0.85,
      "evidence": [
        "frontend/src/features/trading/ConditionalEditor.tsx:16-23",
        "frontend/src/routes/MarketDetail.tsx:62",
        "frontend/src/features/graph/BayesNetGraph.tsx:227-229"
      ],
      "uncertainty": "Whether the callback should also support secondary actions (right-click for context menu, shift-click for multi-select). The task only mentions 'CPT editor integration' which suggests simple navigation for now."
    },
    {
      "question_id": "q7",
      "answer": "Individual modules (d3-force, d3-selection, d3-zoom, d3-drag) are strongly preferred. The frontend has only 4 runtime dependencies (react, react-dom, react-router-dom, @tanstack/react-query). Adding the full d3 bundle (~500KB) would roughly double the bundle size. Individual modules total ~60KB and import only what's needed. The hybrid React+D3 approach further reduces the need for d3-selection since React handles DOM — we primarily need d3-force for simulation, d3-zoom for pan/zoom transforms, and d3-drag for node dragging. d3-selection may still be needed as a peer dependency for d3-zoom and d3-drag event handling.",
      "confidence": 0.95,
      "evidence": [
        "frontend/package.json:dependencies"
      ],
      "uncertainty": "Whether d3-selection is needed as a direct dependency or only as a transitive dependency of d3-zoom/d3-drag. Need to check peer dependency requirements."
    },
    {
      "question_id": "q8",
      "answer": "The existing 11 tests in BayesNetGraph.test.tsx will need significant rework but not complete abandonment. The tests mock useMarkets/useEngineStats and assert on SVG elements/text — the mocking strategy remains valid, but assertions on specific SVG structure will change. Recommended approach: (1) Separate simulation logic into a pure function/hook (useForceGraph) that can be unit-tested without DOM — test that nodes get positions, edges resolve, simulation converges. (2) For component tests, mock the simulation to return fixed positions (bypass async tick) and assert on rendered SVG structure similar to current tests. (3) Keep existing test scenarios (loading state, empty state, truncation, focus highlight, status dots, legend items) as they test business logic, not layout specifics. (4) Drop tests that assert exact pixel positions since force layout is non-deterministic.",
      "confidence": 0.8,
      "evidence": [
        "frontend/src/__tests__/BayesNetGraph.test.tsx:1-332",
        "frontend/src/__tests__/BayesNetGraph.test.tsx:147-154",
        "frontend/src/__tests__/BayesNetGraph.test.tsx:168-178"
      ],
      "uncertainty": "Whether vitest + jsdom properly supports D3's force simulation (it runs requestAnimationFrame-based ticks). May need to mock d3-force's simulation or use fake timers in tests."
    }
  ],
  "assumption_checks": [
    {
      "assumption_id": "a1",
      "verdict": "CORRECT",
      "confidence": 0.95,
      "impact": "Individual D3 modules are clearly the right choice. Frontend has only 4 runtime deps, and the hybrid React+D3 approach minimizes which D3 modules are even needed. Install d3-force, d3-zoom, d3-drag, and d3-selection (as peer dep)."
    },
    {
      "assumption_id": "a2",
      "verdict": "CORRECT",
      "confidence": 0.9,
      "impact": "The NodeWithDetail pattern (useMarket per node for lazy detail loading) and React Query integration require React to own the DOM. D3 should only compute positions and handle zoom/drag interactions via useEffect hooks on refs."
    },
    {
      "assumption_id": "a3",
      "verdict": "CORRECT",
      "confidence": 0.8,
      "impact": "useMarkets provides nodes, useEngineStats provides cliques. No new endpoints needed for the graph itself. However, directed edges are NOT available from any existing endpoint — see a4. If directed edges are required, a new endpoint reading CONDITIONAL_MARGINALS would be needed."
    },
    {
      "assumption_id": "a4",
